Use conditional compilation or the MAUI `#if` platform directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

#if ANDROID
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();
#elif IOS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();
#elif WINDOWS
    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();
#endif

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- `ANDROID`, `IOS`, and `WINDOWS` are predefined symbols set by the MAUI build targets — no extra config needed.
- Place each platform implementation under `Platforms/<platform>/` so it only compiles for that target (the default `.csproj` already scopes those folders).
- If you prefer avoiding `#if` directives, you can instead use **partial classes** or the `DeviceInfo.Platform` check at runtime with a factory pattern — but conditional compilation is the standard MAUI approach and catches errors at build time.
